"In chronic kidney disease, kidney function gradually decreases over months or years. In the early stages, most patients' bodies compensate or adapt to metabolic abnormalities, so they are relatively asymptomatic. However, symptoms of uremia or water retention begin to develop when kidney function is severely degraded.What are the symptoms of chronic kidney disease?

Symptoms of chronic kidney disease vary depending on the degree of kidney damage. Chronic kidney disease is divided into five stages according to kidney function and glomerular filtration rate (GFR). The glomerular filtration rate can be calculated with serum creatinine and must normally exceed 90 mL/min.
Stage 1 of chronic kidney disease (90-100% kidney function

Stage 1 Chronic kidney disease refers to cases where glomerular filtration rates are 90 mL/min/1.73 m2 or higher, but only tests such as proteinuria are accompanied; structural damage to the kidneys in X-rays, ultrasound, MRI or CT; or family history of polycystic kidney disease. There are no symptoms you feel at this stage.
Chronic kidney disease stage 2 (60-89% kidney function)

In stage 2 chronic kidney disease or mild chronic kidney disease, the glomerular filtration rate is 60-89 mL/min/1.73 m2. There are usually no symptoms at this stage, but some patients urinate frequently at night, have high blood pressure, normal or small increases in serum creatinine, or have abnormal urine tests."
